# iPhone hotplug rules.
#
# Plug-in is NOT handled here anymore: the always-on display daemon
# (iosbackupmachine.service) owns the e-ink for the whole uptime and polls for a
# connected device itself. Restarting it on plug would tear down the EPD owner
# mid-render — the SPI contention this refactor removes.
#
# Removal still fires a one-shot that stops a running idevicebackup2 so the
# daemon notices the unplug promptly (it renders the interrupted/idle screen).
ACTION=="remove", SUBSYSTEM=="usb", ENV{DEVTYPE}=="usb_device", \
  ENV{PRODUCT}=="5ac/*", \
  RUN+="/bin/systemctl --no-block start unplug-notify.service"

# Plug-in fires a guarded one-shot that re-scans usbmuxd. usbmuxd runs
# persistently here but doesn't get libusb hotplug events, so a device plugged
# after boot stays invisible to idevice_* until usbmuxd restarts. The one-shot
# restarts usbmuxd only when the kernel sees an Apple device that usbmux doesn't,
# and never during a backup. It does NOT touch the display daemon (the reason
# add-handling was dropped before), so the EPD owner is undisturbed.
ACTION=="add", SUBSYSTEM=="usb", ENV{DEVTYPE}=="usb_device", \
  ENV{PRODUCT}=="5ac/*", \
  RUN+="/bin/systemctl --no-block start usbmux-refresh.service"
